## Migration: `TimedExecutor` â†’ .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern with a **ThreadAbortException-as-control-flow** catch:

| API | Line | Replacement |
|-----|------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Called when `Join(timeout)` fails | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter(timeout)` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Swallows the abort | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Keeps thread alive after abort | Remove â€” not needed with cooperative cancellation |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime. The thread will **never** be stopped â€” your timeout is silently broken.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. Cooperative cancellation requires the work to cooperate.**
Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation does **not** forcibly kill the delegate. If `work()` is a tight CPU loop or a blocking syscall, it will keep running after the timeout â€” the caller just stops waiting. To fix this, pass the token into the work:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Then callers check the token at regular checkpoints:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return results;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**2. `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`.** Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer leaks since `CancelAfter` starts an internal timer.

**3. `Task.WaitAsync` abandons â€” it doesn't kill.** The underlying `Task.Run` continues on a thread-pool thread even after the timeout fires. If `work()` holds resources (DB connections, file handles), those stay open until the delegate naturally completes. Use `CancellationToken.Register` for cleanup if needed.

**4. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`.** The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch your own timeout, not cancellation from an outer scope.

**5. If the work truly cannot cooperate** (e.g., third-party library with no cancellation support), the only safe option in .NET 8 is to move it to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort`.
